    1. ‌INTRODUCTION


      With the rapid evolution that software development is facing today, it is important to pay special attention to making processes as efficient and optimized as possible. The adoption of DevOps practices has become an answer to offer high quality software and accelerate the deployment of applications, promoting and improving collaboration between development and operations teams, placing main focus on automation, continuous integration and continuous deployment.

      This report provides an overview of implementing a DevOps pipeline in Microsoft Azure for the development and deployment of a simple calculator API using Spring Boot.

      The project aims to address the following objectives:


  • Develop a simple calculator API using Spring Boot.

  • Deploy a DevOps pipeline to automate build, test, and deployment processes.

  • Use Microsoft Azure services for containerization, deployment, monitoring, and analysis.

  • Offer better communication between team members by integrating the pipeline with Slack.


    This report will dive into the tools and services used in the DevOps process, providing information on the pipeline architecture, implementation details, challenges faced, and lessons learned throughout this development. project.

    By documenting our experience, remains and learnings, we hope to contribute to a broader understanding of DevOps methodologies and that our work will motivate others who are beginning their learning in efficient and automated software delivery.

    1. ‌PROJECT BACKGROUND


      The application developed is a simple REST (REpresentational State Transfer) calculator API (Application Programming Interface) named “simple-calculator”. It will have serval capabilities such as arithmetic functions stated below:

  • Addition

  • Subtraction

  • Multiplication

  • Division

  • Finding modulus

  • Concatenation

  • Finding powers

  • Finding square

  • Finding square root

  • Log functions.


The project is available at https://github.com/RuFerdZ/simple-calculator (Private repository)


Public Reference repository: https://github.com/yoliRios/simple-calculator


  1. ‌TOOLS & TECHNOLOGIES

    1. ‌General Tools

      • Git – Used for version controlling our codebase.

      • GitHub – The Source Code Management platform (SCM) used to store the code.

      • Jenkins – The automation platform coordinates our CICD (Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment) pipeline.

      • Docker – The tool used to containerize and ship our code.

      • SonarQube – A tool used to quality check our code on pre-defined configurations based on several factors.

      • Slack – The business messaging app used to send notifications/alerts regarding our pipelines.

      • Postman – API platform used to test and document our simple-calculator API.

      • Newman – Postman's Command Line Interface (CLI) collection runner to test our live APIs.

      • Microsoft Azure – The cloud platform we use to deploy and manage our API.

    2. ‌Microsoft Azure Services

      The following Azure services have been used in successfully implementing the CICD pipeline.


      • Microsoft Entra ID (formerly Azure Active Directory) – Used to register 3rd party applications/users to be able to use Azure services.

        • Allowing Jenkins to access Azure resources.

        • Creating users to access the Azure portal.

      • Azure CLI – This Azure command-line tool allows users to execute commands on Azure resources.

      • Azure Container Registry (ACR) – This service stores our images (acts as our image repository).

      • Azure App Services – This service is a fully managed service for building and deploying scalable web applications and APIs directly from docker images.

      • Azure Monitor Workspaces – This service provides a centralized location for collecting, analyzing, and acting on telemetry data from multiple sources.

      • Azure Log Analytics Workspaces - A standalone service that provides advanced analytics and querying capabilities for log data collected from various sources.

      • Azure Managed Grafana – A fully managed service for managing analytics and monitoring all applications in one place.

    3. ‌Java Code

      package com.backend.calculator; import org.slf4j.Logger;

      import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

      import org.springframework.boot.logging.LoggingSystemFactory; import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping; import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping; import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestParam; import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;


      @RestController @RequestMapping("/calc") public class CalculatorController {


      Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(CalculatorController.class);

      // Addtion function @GetMapping("/add")

      public int add(@RequestParam int a, @RequestParam int b) { logger.info("Adding {} and {}", a, b);

      return a + b;

      }


      @GetMapping("/subtract")

      public int subtract(@RequestParam int a, @RequestParam int b) { logger.info("Subtracting {} and {}", a, b);

      return a - b;

      }


      @GetMapping("/multiply")

      public int multiply(@RequestParam int a, @RequestParam int b) { logger.info("Multiplying {} and {}", a, b);

      return a * b;

      }

      @GetMapping("/divide")

      public int divide(@RequestParam int a, @RequestParam int b) { logger.info("Dividing {} and {}", a, b);

      return a / b;

      }


      @GetMapping("/remainder")

      public int remainder(@RequestParam int a, @RequestParam int b) { logger.info("Finding remainder {} and {}", a, b);

      return a % b;

      }


      @GetMapping("/concat")

      public String concat(@RequestParam String a, @RequestParam String b) { logger.info("Concatenating {} and {}", a, b);

      return a + b;

      }


      @GetMapping("/power")

      public long power(@RequestParam double a, @RequestParam double b) { logger.info("Finding power of {} and {}", a, b);

      return (long) Math.pow(a, b);

      }

      @GetMapping("/square")

      public long square(@RequestParam double a) { logger.info("Finding square of {}", a);

      return (long) Math.pow(a, 2);

      }


      @GetMapping("/sqrt")

      public double sqrt(@RequestParam double a) { logger.info("Finding square-root of {}", a); return Math.sqrt(a);

      }


      @GetMapping("/log")

      public double log(@RequestParam double a) { logger.info("Finding log of {}", a);

      return Math.log(a);

      }

      }

    5. ‌Integration with CI/CD Pipeline

      As mentioned in 6.1. the /env directory holds the Jenkins jobs in an environmentally specific manner. GitHub webhooks are used to trigger the specific job when there is a change on a primary branch.



      ‌Figure 2: GitHub webhooks.


      After we enable it on GitHub, we need to update the Jenkins pipeline job to capture triggers and to run the Jenkins CICD job on that specific primary branch.

      Firstly, we need to enable “GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling” under the Build Triggers in the Jenkins job.



      ‌Figure 3: Enable GitHub hook trigger.


      Next, we need to set up the branch and the Jenkins job file in the Pipeline section on the job. In the below image we have set to run the job for the “dev” branch.

      We set it to get the job script from SCM by setting the definition to “Pipeline script from SCM”.

      Next, we provide the repository URL and the credentials (since it’s private). Then we state the branch to watch for any changes and then we specify the location of the script file.


      ‌Figure 4: Set pipeline script.

  3. ‌ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW


    1. ‌High-level Architecture Diagram

      The diagram below gives an overview of the architecture of our CICD pipeline.



      ‌Figure 5: Architecture Diagram


      Note: Changes to original proposal:

      • We have merged the CI and CD jobs as one single job.

      • We have used Azure App Services for the deployment instead of Azure Container Apps.

    2. ‌Interaction and Flow

      As per the above architecture diagram, all features and fixes will be merged to the dev branch, which will in turn trigger the dev Jenkins pipeline job on the Jenkins server via the webhook.

      This will start the “CICD job”, which will run code quality checks via SonarQube, run the unit tests, build the docker image and push the image to the Azure Container Registry (ACR) via Azure CLI. This marks the end of the Continuous Integration part.

      In the Continuous Deployment stage (still in the same pipeline), it will get the image from ACR and deploy it on the environment specific Azure App Service via Azure CLI.

      Once the deployment is completed, the CICD job will send a notification to the environment specific Slack channel about the status of the CICD job.

      If the deployment is successful, it will trigger the “API Testing job” which will import our environment specific Postman collection, from our Postman workspace to the command line API testing tool Newman and run all the API tests on the deployed application.

      Once the tests are completed, the API testing job will send a notification to the environment specific Slack channel about the status of the test results.

      This marks the successful deployment of our dev environment.


      Developers will to manual testing on this deployment to see everything works fine, and then they will merge it to the staging branch which will trigger the pipeline for the staging environment. It will follow the same steps for CICD and testing as mentioned for the dev environment above.

      QA’s and/or product owners will run tests on this deployment. Once the staging deployment is tested and is scheduled to go live, it will be merge to the master branch (production environment). This will trigger the production pipeline and will go through the same stages as above dev pipeline.

      We have integrated Azure Log Analytics Workspaces to collect logs from our Azure App Services, and Azure Monitor to monitor our containers and visualize them through Azure Managed Grafana service.

      2. ‌Azure Resource Group

        Name: fusion-x


      3. ‌Jenkins Server

        Name: jenkins-server


        Virtual machine type: B2ms (2 vCPUs, 8 GiB memory) DNS: https://fx-jenkins.canadacentral.cloudapp.azure.com

        • 8080 – Jenkins server

        • 9000 – SonarQube server


          Server Setup Steps

          1. Open ports 8080 and 9000

            1. Open ports 8080 and 9000 so that the public users can access the Jenkins and SonarQube Servers.

              Updated in the Virtual machine’s Network Settings section.



              ‌Figure 7: Add inbound rules for port 8080 and 9000.


          2. Update Ubuntu packages.

            1. Update ubuntu package library.

              $ sudo apt-get update

          3. Install Java

            1. Install open JDK 17


              $ sudo apt install openjdk-17-jre -y


            2. Verify installation.

              $ java --version


          4. Setup Jenkins

            1. Download Jenkins Repository key.


              $ sudo wget -O /usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/jenkins.io-2023.key


            2. Add the Jenkins repository to the system's package sources.


              $ echo deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc] https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/ | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list >

              /dev/null


            3. Update the package library again to include information from the newly added Jenkins repository.

              .

              $ sudo apt-get update


            4. Install Jenkins.


              $ sudo apt-get install jenkins


            5. Enable Jenkins on startup.


              $ sudo systemctl enable jenkins

          5. Setup Azure CLI

            1. Install Azure CLI

              $ sudo apt install azure-cli -y


            2. Login to Azure CLI from the virtual machine

              $ az login


          6. Setup SonarQube

            1. Setup PostgreSQL

              1. Add the PostgreSQL repository.

                $ sudo sh -c 'echo "deb http://apt.postgresql.org/pub/repos/apt/

                `lsb_release -cs` pgdg main" /etc/apt/sources.list.d/pgdg.list'


              2. Add the PostgreSQL signing key.

                $ wget -q https://www.postgresql.org/media/keys... -O - | sudo apt-key

                add –


              3. Install PostgreSQL

                $ sudo apt install postgresql postgresql-contrib -y


              4. Enable the database server to start automatically on reboot.

                $ sudo systemctl enable postgresql


              5. Start the database server.

                $ sudo systemctl start postgresql


              6. Change the default PostgreSQL password.

                $ sudo passwd postgres


              7. Switch to the postgres user.

                $ su – postgres


              8. Create a user named sonar.

                $ createuser sonar

              9. Log in to PostgreSQL.

                $ psql


              10. Set a password for the sonar user.

                psql > ALTER USER sonar WITH ENCRYPTED password 'my_password';


              11. Create a sonarqube database and set the owner to sonar.

                psql > CREATE DATABASE sonarqube OWNER sonar;


              12. Grant all the privileges on the sonarqube database to the sonar user.

                psql > GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE sonarqube to sonar;


              13. Exit PostgreSQL.

                psql > \q


              14. Return to your non-root sudo user account.

                $ exit


            2. Setup SonarQube

              1. Install the zip utility, which is needed to unzip the SonarQube files.

                $ sudo apt-get install zip -y


              2. Download the SonarQube distribution files.


                $ sudo wget https://binaries.sonarsource.com/Distribution/sonarqube/sonarqube- 10.4.1.88267.zip

              3. Unzip the downloaded file.

                $ sudo unzip sonarqube-10.4.1.88267.zip


              4. Move the unzipped files to /opt/sonarqube directory.


                $ sudo mv sonarqube-9.6.1.59531 sonarqube

                $ sudo mv sonarqube /opt/


              5. Create a sonar group.

                $ sudo groupadd sonar


              6. Create a sonar user and set /opt/sonarqube as the home directory.

                $ sudo useradd -d /opt/sonarqube -g sonar sonar


              7. Grant the sonar user access to the /opt/sonarqube directory.

                $ sudo chown sonar:sonar /opt/sonarqube -R


              8. Edit the SonarQube configuration file.

                $ sudo nano /opt/sonarqube/conf/sonar.properties


                Find the following lines:


                #sonar.jdbc.username= #sonar.jdbc.password=


                Uncomment the lines, and add the database user and password you created in Step 5.a.x.


                sonar.jdbc.username=sonar sonar.jdbc.password=my_ password


                Below those two lines, add the sonar.jdbc.url.

                sonar.jdbc.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/sonarqube


                Save and exit the file.


              9. Edit the sonar script file.


                $ sudo nano /opt/sonarqube/bin/linux-x86-64/sonar.sh

                About 50 lines down, locate this line:


                #RUN_AS_USER=


                Uncomment the line and change it to:


                RUN_AS_USER=sonar


                Save and exit the file.


              10. Create a systemd service file to start SonarQube at system boot.


                $ sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/sonar.service


                Paste the following lines to the file.


                [Unit]

                Description=SonarQube service After=syslog.target network.target


                [Service] Type=forking


                ExecStart=/opt/sonarqube/bin/linux-x86-64/sonar.sh start ExecStop=/opt/sonarqube/bin/linux-x86-64/sonar.sh stop


                User=sonar Group=sonar Restart=always


                LimitNOFILE=65536 LimitNPROC=4096


                [Install]

                WantedBy=multi-user.target


                Save and exit the file.


              11. Enable the SonarQube service to run at system startup.


                $ sudo systemctl enable sonar


              12. Start the SonarQube service.


                $ sudo systemctl start sonar


              13. Check the service status.


                $ sudo systemctl status sonar


            3. Modify Kernel System Limits


              SonarQube uses Elasticsearch to store its indices in an MMap FS directory. It requires some changes to the system defaults.


              1. Edit the sysctl configuration file.


                $ sudo nano /etc/sysctl.conf


                Add the following lines.


                vm.max_map_count=262144 fs.file-max=65536

                ulimit -n 65536

                ulimit -u 4096

                Save and exit the file.

              2. Reboot the system to apply the changes

                $ sudo reboot

          7. Setup Docker


          1. Install Docker

            $ sudo apt-get install docker.io -y


          2. Add current user to docker group.

            $ sudo usermod -aG docker $USER


          3. Add Jenkins user to docker group.

          $ sudo usermod -aG docker Jenkins

  4. ‌CICD PIPELINE WORKFLOW


    1. ‌Code Commit and Version Control

      GitHub was used as our Source Control Management platform to maintain our codebase.



      ‌Figure 26: GitHub repository.


      1. ‌Branching Structure

        There are 3 primary branches:


        • master

        • staging

        • dev


          The “master” branch is the main branch of our project, and it is that is deployed on production. Then we have our “staging” branch which is deployed on our Staging server for QA testing where the selected features that should go live reside. Next, we have the “dev branch, which is used for integration of different fixes or features. This branch is used for development testing and integration testing purposes.

          All these 3 primary branches are protected from direct pushes and also to only merged by pull request which should be approved by the code owner.

          The “dev” branch will be branched-out to specific feature or fix branches unless it’s a hotfix that needs to be merged to the “master” branch directly.

          The following branch naming convention is followed:


        • Feature – feat/<branch-name>

        • Fix – fix/< branch-name >

        • Hotfix – hotfix/< branch-name >


      2. ‌Commit formats.

        When committing the code, the following commit messaging convention was followed:


        • “<type >: <commit-message>” Example

          1. $ git commit -m “fix: fixed missing } on line 1 of Application.java”


    2. ‌CICD Job

      The overall workflow utilizes Continuous Integration (CI) and Continuous Delivery (CD) processes within a Jenkins environment. Commits to three primary branches initiate the CICD process.



      Figure 5: CICD Job Workflow.

      We have a Jenkins CICD file and a Jenkins API testing file for each environment.


      The CICD Pipeline is the same for each environment except the target registries and applications for deployment.

      pipeline { agent any


      tools {

      gradle 'Gradle 8.7'

      }


      stages {

      stage('Create build executable') { steps {

      sh 'chmod +x gradlew' // Make gradlew executable

      }

      }


      stage('SonarQube Analysis') { steps () {

      sh "./gradlew sonar"

      }

      }

      stage('Running Unit tests') { steps {

      sh './gradlew test' // Run tests

      }

      }


      stage('Docker Build') { steps {

      sh 'docker build -t simplecalculatorregistry.azurecr.io/calculator-api-dev:latest .'

      }

      }


      stage('Push to Azure Container Registry') { steps {

      azureCLI commands: [

      [exportVariablesString: '', script: 'az acr login -n simpleCalculatorRegistry'], [exportVariablesString: '', script: 'docker push

      simplecalculatorregistry.azurecr.io/calculator-api-dev:latest']

      ],

      principalCredentialId: 'azure-jenkins-app-auth'

      }

      }


      stage('Deploy to Azure App Services') { steps {

      azureCLI commands: [

      [exportVariablesString: '', script: 'az acr login -n simpleCalculatorRegistry'], [exportVariablesString: '', script: 'az webapp restart --name simple-calculator-api-dev --

      resource-group fusion-x'],

      [exportVariablesString: '', script: 'az webapp config container set --name simple- calculator-api-dev --resource-group fusion-x --docker-custom-image-name simplecalculatorregistry.azurecr.io/calculator-api-dev:latest']

      ],

      principalCredentialId: 'azure-jenkins-app-auth'

      }

      }


      stage('Clean Workspace') { steps {

      // Clean up Docker image

      sh 'docker rmi -f simplecalculatorregistry.azurecr.io/calculator-api-dev:latest'

      }

      }

      }

      post {

      always { script {

      def pipelineStatus = currentBuild.currentResult == null ? 'RUNNING' : currentBuild.currentResult

      def color = ''

      switch (pipelineStatus) { case 'SUCCESS':

      color = '#36a64f' // Green break

      case 'FAILURE':

      color = '#ff0000' // Red break

      case 'ABORTED':

      color = '#bdbdbd' // Grey break

      default:

      color = '#ffbf00' // Yellow break

      *CI/CD Pipeline Status Update*

      *Job Name:* ${env.JOB_NAME}

      *Build Number:* ${env.BUILD_NUMBER}

      *Build URL:* ${env.BUILD_URL}

      *Status:* ${pipelineStatus} """

      fallback: "CI/CD Pipeline Pipeline Status Update - ${env.JOB_NAME} -

      ${pipelineStatus}",

      text: slackMessage

      ]


      slackSend channel: 'fx-dev' , attachments: [attachment], tokenCredentialId: 'slack-auth'

      }

      }

      success {

      build job: 'Automated API Test Jobs/dev-api-testing'

      }

      }

      Both pipelines will be explained in detail in the following sections.

      1. ‌Create Executable gradlew.

        At the beginning of the pipeline, we set the Jenkins agent to any, and stated the build tool we are going to use in the pipeline.

        As the first stage we need to make the gradlew file an executable file.



        Figure 6: Stage - Make gradlew executable.


      2. ‌Code Quality Check

        Next, SonarQube is used to analyze and ensure code quality.




      3. ‌Run Unit Tests

        Figure 7: Stage - SonarQube Analysis.

        Next, we run the unit tests to ensure that all the defined logic is working as expected.



        ‌Figure 27: Stage - Run unit tests.


      4. ‌Containerization

        A Dockerfile is used to create a container image. This Dockerfile is responsible for configuring an environment to create and run a Spring Boot application with Gradle inside a Docker container. Here are the following keywords from it.

        • Keyword: FROM


          • Begins by using the openjdk:17-alpine image as the base. This provides a Java 17 runtime built upon a lightweight Alpine Linux distribution.

        • Keyword: WORKDIR


          • Sets the working directory inside the container to /app. All subsequent instructions will execute within this context.

        • Keyword: COPY


          • Copy the necessary Gradle files (build.gradle, settings.gradle, gradlew) to the container's

            /app directory.


          • Copy the Gradle container (gradle) properties to the container's /app/gradle directory.


          • Copy the application source code (src) to the container's /app/src directory.


        • Keyword: RUN


          • Run the Gradle build command (./gradlew build) inside the container to build the app.


        • Keyword: EXPOSE


          • Exposes port 8080, which is typically used by Spring Boot applications.


        • Keyword: CMD

          • Specifies the command to run the application, which runs the JAR file (calculator-0.0.1- SNAPSHOT.jar) located in the build/libs directory.



            Figure 8: Dockerfile.


            Next, we build the docker image from the docker file locally (Jenkins Server).



            Figure 9: Stage - Docker Build Job


            Next, we will login to the Azure Container Registry (ACR) and push the built image into the registry.



            Figure 10: Stage - The image is pushed to Azure Container Registry (ACR).


            This marks the end of the Continuous Integration (CI) phase.


      5. ‌Deployment to Azure


        This job handles the deployment of the container image to an Azure App Service. It begins by logging into the 'simpleCalculatorRegistry' Azure Container Registry.

        Then, it restarts the 'simple-calculator-api-dev' web app within the 'fusion-x' resource group.


        Finally, it updates the web app's container image to the latest version located at simplecalculatorregistry.azurecr.io/calculator-api-dev:latest'.



        Figure 11: Stage - Deployment to Azure App Services.


      6. ‌Cleaning up the Workspace

        In the docker build process, we create images locally on the Jenkins Server. Over time the Jenkins server will run out of storage.

        We implemented a stage to clean up the images created during the CICD job pipeline at the end of the pipeline.



        ‌Figure 28: Stage - Cleanup workspace.


      7. ‌Post CICD Job tasks.

        Once the CICD pipeline execution completes (success/fail) it will proceed with the “post” stage do additional stages no matter the status of the pipeline.



        ‌Figure 29:Post stage – CICD pipeline.


        This job sends a status update to a Slack channel after the build process is complete. Here's how it works:


        • Status Determination: The job determines the status of the build (SUCCESS, FAILURE, ABORTED, or other).

        • Color Coding: A color is assigned based on the status: green for success, red for failure, grey for aborted, and yellow for any other status.

        • Slack Message: A Slack message is constructed, including the job name, build number, build URL, and the determined status.

        • Notification: The message, along with a colored attachment indicating the status, is sent to the Slack channel 'fx-dev' using the 'slack-auth' credential.


    3. ‌Post-Deployment Testing

      A dedicated API testing job, using Postman and Newman, executes logical tests against API endpoints.


      Figure 12: Stage - Post Deployment Testing Job


      This job automates the testing of the API and only executes after new deployments. It introduces a 2-minute delay in the 'Waiting for Deployment' stage, ensuring any deployment processes are complete before proceeding. It leverages the Newman tool and our Postman to execute the tests.

      Once the testing is done, it will send a notification on slack regarding the status of the test run on the specific environment channel.



      ‌Figure 30: Post stage – API testing pipeline.

      As discussed in sections 6.2.6 and 6.3, we set up our Slack channels receive notifications on:


      • CICD job (success/failure)

  5. ‌RESULTS AND BENEFITS


    1. Development speed


      Before automation, it takes a significant amount of time to release a new feature. With DevOps and the CI/CD pipeline implemented, we can reduce the time drastically to release new features into live. This will also increase the frequency of delivery, which contributes to the speed the application has been delivered.

    2. Increased quality


      The CICD pipeline has a positive impact on the quality of application delivery. This is achieved by automating testing scenarios to identify bugs at an early stage in the development process.

    3. Reduction in downtime


      Automating the deployments has reduced manual delivery of the software after an incident has occurred as manual deployments often result in error prone configurations.

    4. Increased efficiency


      We were able to see increased efficiency between development and operations. Since automation, time is saved, thus giving the teams more time to focus on important things.

    5. Team collaboration and communication


    Integration with business messaging tools, such as Slack, for team communication, notifications and alerts each with their own channels. Real-time communication increased team efficiency and reduced response time to incidents.

  8. ‌CHALLENGES AND LESSONS LEARNT


    1. We encountered an issue where Azure app service was not deployed even though continuous deployment was enabled, and pipeline succeeded in running the container. It only worked once the App service was restarted before the deployment. To address this, a solution was implemented within the pipeline to automatically restart the app service before the deployment.


    2. Another issue arose with the excessive RAM usage of SonarQube on the Jenkins server. This resulted in slowed job performance and occasional server crashes due to high RAM utilization. To mitigate this issue, we increased the RAM capacity from 4GB to 8GB, as Docker, Jenkins, and SonarQube were concurrently running.

      The recommended minimum requirement for these is as follows:

      • Docker container – 2 GB

      • Jenkins – 1 GB

      • SonarQube – 2GB


        Therefore, 8GB was allocated for RAM.


        In addition, we edited the kernel system limits file to cap the SonarQube memory utilization instead of utilizing the entire available memory possible.

    3. The next issue we faced was in an instance where all the 3 pipelines were running at once. Each pipeline has 2 jobs, therefore altogether it will be 6 jobs. By default, Jenkins has set for only 2 parallel build executors to run, we had to increase this to 6 to accommodate any chances of all jobs running to gather without getting halted/aborted along the way.

  9. ‌FUTURE RECOMMENDATIONS


    It is essential to identify the opportunities for further improvement of our project. In this section, the key future recommendations aimed at enhancing DevOps practices are outlined. These recommendations encompass strategies tailored to elevate operational efficiency, enhance reliability, and ultimately deliver enhanced outcomes.

    • Auto scaling:

      Auto-scaling is a critical feature for modern DevOps projects to efficiently manage resources and ensure optimal performance under varying traffic conditions, to address both high and low traffic scenarios effectively. When the auto scaling feature is implemented, varying traffic levels will be managed effectively, ensuring optimal performance, and enhancing scalability and reliability of the system.


    • K8s for managing clusters:

      When the K8s clusters are implemented in the projects it offers wide range of benefits such as streamlined orchestration, scalability, high availability, resource efficiency, and self-healing capabilities. Auto healing feature is important in DevOps project as it automatically detects container failures and restarts the containers which minimizes the downtime and enhances reliability.


    • Optimizing the CICD pipeline and the testing

    This can be implemented by running parallel tests to reduce overall testing time, incremental builds to only rebuild and test the changed parts of the code, instead of entire code and optimize dependency management to ensure efficient downloading and caching of dependencies.

  10. ‌CONCLUSION


The use of DevOps processes in the development of this project has allowed us to gain a deeper understanding of this practice as well as each of the tools that we use and configure to successfully automate the integration, deployment, and testing of the API calculator. We were able to see how much faster the development, integration, deployment, and testing cycles were compared to manual processes; this experience provides us with a solid criterion for the importance of implementing DevOps practices and how this can optimize work times, team communication, and workflow.

It should be noted that the realization of this project was full of challenges, such as learning curves associated with the use of new technologies and issues with tool configuration and integration, but with effort, collaboration, and teamwork, we were able to overcome them and make this opportunity an enriching experience not only from a technical point of view but also from a teamwork and collaboration perspective.

Looking ahead, we are eager to continue learning and improving in the adoption of DevOps practices, enhancing our analysis and monitoring capabilities, process improvements, tool selection, and configuration, with the goal of increasing our success and ensuring the delivery of high-quality software when the customer needs it, and the current market demands it.
